<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,701,2007]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis box="[199,350,741,766]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Distribution.</emphasis>
Western Atlantic – Florida Keys to 
<collectingCountry box="[798,1053,741,767]" name="Trinidad and Tobago" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Trinidad and Tobago</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[1121,1219,741,767]" name="Curaçao" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Curaçao</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Udekem" pageId="17" pageNumber="44" refString="Udekem d'Acoz, C. d'. (2000) Redescription of Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879) based on topotypical specimens, with remarks on Lysmata seticaudata (Risso, 1816) (Decapoda, Caridea, Hippolytidae). Crustaceana, 73 (6), 719 - 735." type="journal article" year="2000">
Udekem d’Acoz 
<number box="[151,215,781,807]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<collectingCountry box="[237,309,781,807]" name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Brazil</collectingCountry>
– Pernambuco (Ramos-Porto 
<emphasis box="[675,737,781,806]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[747,809,781,807]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1995.0">1995</number>
), Espírito Santo, and Rio de Janeiro (
<bibRefCitation author="Christoffersen" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="17" pageNumber="39" refString="Christoffersen, M. L. (1998) Malacostraca. Eucarida. Caridea. Crangonoidea and Alpheoidea (Except Glyphocrangonidae and Crangonidae). In: Young, P. S. (Ed.), Catalogue of Crustacea of Brazil. Museu Nacional, Rio de Janeiro, pp. 351 - 372." type="book chapter" year="1998">
Christoffersen 
<number box="[151,214,821,847]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1998.0">1998</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,701,2007]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Habitat: In seagrass flats studded with the corals 
<taxonomicName box="[775,860,861,886]" class="Anthozoa" family="Poritidae" genus="Porites" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scleractinia" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[775,860,861,886]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Porites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[917,1057,861,886]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Pocillopara</emphasis>
, but some associated with algae on rocky shores, and a few with reef corals. From shallow waters to 
<quantity box="[952,1012,901,927]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="m" value="22.0">22 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Chace" box="[1027,1172,901,927]" pageId="17" pageNumber="39" refString="Chace Jr., F. A. (1972) The shrimps of the Smithsonian-Bredin Caribbean Expeditions with a summary of the West Indian shallow-water species (Crustacea: Decapoda: Natantia). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 98, 1 - 179." type="journal article" year="1972">
Chace 
<number box="[1109,1172,901,927]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1972.0">1972</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,701,2007]" box="[199,590,941,967]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis box="[199,512,941,966]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Previous records in Bahia.</emphasis>
None.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,701,2007]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis box="[199,309,981,1006]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Remarks.</emphasis>
Another shrimp species rarely recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[863,935,981,1007]" name="Brazil" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Christoffersen" box="[952,1193,981,1007]" pageId="17" pageNumber="39" refString="Christoffersen, M. L. (1980) Taxonomia e distribuicao dos Alpheoida (Crustacea, Decapoda, Natantia) do Brasil, Uruguai e norte da Argentina, incluindo consideracoes sobre a divisao do sul do continente em provincias biogeograficas marinhas. PhD Thesis, Universidade de Sao Paulo, 467 pp." type="book" year="1980">
Christoffersen 
<number box="[1131,1193,981,1007]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1980.0">1980</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; Ramos–Porto 
<emphasis box="[1375,1436,981,1006]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[151,214,1021,1047]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1995.0">1995</number>
). 
<bibRefCitation box="[234,511,1021,1047]" pageId="17" pageNumber="44" refString="Udekem d'Acoz, C. d'. (2000) Redescription of Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879) based on topotypical specimens, with remarks on Lysmata seticaudata (Risso, 1816) (Decapoda, Caridea, Hippolytidae). Crustaceana, 73 (6), 719 - 735." type="journal article">
Udekem d’Acoz (
<number box="[442,504,1021,1047]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="2000.0">2000</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
redescribed 
<taxonomicName box="[660,818,1021,1046]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intermedia">
<emphasis box="[660,818,1021,1046]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">L. intermedia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on topotypical specimens from the Dry 
<collectingCountry name="Haiti" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Tortugas</collectingCountry>
, Florida, also reviewing the previous records of this species. Comparison of samples collected in the Azores with the topotypical material, allowed him to establish that Azorean material attributed to 
<taxonomicName authority="Rathbun, 1901" authorityName="Rathbun" authorityYear="1901" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intermedia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">L. intermedia</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Rathbun" box="[205,383,1141,1167]" pageId="17" pageNumber="43" refString="Rathbun, M. J. (1901) The Brachyura and Macrura of Porto Rico. Bulletin of the United States Fish Commission, 20 (2), 1 - 127." type="journal article" year="1901">
Rathbun, 
<number box="[323,383,1141,1167]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1901.0">1901</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
is in fact 
<taxonomicName authority="Risso, 1816" authorityName="Risso" authorityYear="1816" box="[513,852,1141,1167]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seticaudata">
<emphasis box="[513,680,1141,1166]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">L. seticaudata</emphasis>
(Risso, 
<number box="[781,843,1141,1167]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1816.0">1816</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
, a similar, warm-water species. According to the author, the records from the Galapagos and 
<collectingCountry box="[668,790,1181,1207]" name="Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Ascension</collectingCountry>
islands (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Chace" box="[942,1086,1181,1207]" pageId="17" pageNumber="39" refString="Chace Jr., F. A. (1972) The shrimps of the Smithsonian-Bredin Caribbean Expeditions with a summary of the West Indian shallow-water species (Crustacea: Decapoda: Natantia). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 98, 1 - 179." type="journal article" year="1972">
Chace 
<number box="[1024,1086,1181,1207]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1972.0">1972</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Manning" box="[1098,1384,1181,1207]" pageId="17" pageNumber="41" refString="Manning, R. B &amp; Chace, Jr., F. A. (1990) Decapod and Stomatopod Crustacea from Ascension Island, South Atlantic Ocean. Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 503, 1 - 91." type="journal article" year="1990">
Manning &amp; Chace 
<number box="[1324,1384,1181,1207]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1990.0">1990</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) are also questionable and are based on a misidentifications.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,701,2007]" lastBlockId="18.[151,1436,152,298]" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
In general appearance, our material (ovigerous female, 7.1 mm CL) agrees with the description provided by 
<bibRefCitation box="[188,470,1301,1327]" pageId="17" pageNumber="44" refString="Udekem d'Acoz, C. d'. (2000) Redescription of Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879) based on topotypical specimens, with remarks on Lysmata seticaudata (Risso, 1816) (Decapoda, Caridea, Hippolytidae). Crustaceana, 73 (6), 719 - 735." type="journal article">
Udekem d’Acoz (
<number box="[396,461,1301,1327]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="2000.0">2000</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. The rostrum has 
<number box="[678,693,1301,1327]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="7.0">7</number>
dorsal (
<number box="[789,804,1301,1327]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="3.0">3</number>
behind the orbit) and 
<number box="[1063,1077,1301,1327]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="2.0">2</number>
ventral teeth (
<figureCitation box="[1246,1326,1301,1327]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,255,1770,1794]" captionTargetBox="[151,1429,356,1724]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,354,1746]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879), ovigerous (MZUESC  714), from Camamu Bay, Bahia, Brazil. A. anterior region of carapace, lateral view; B. carapace and cephalic appendages, dorsal view; C. right outer antennular flagellum; D. abdomen and telson, lateral view. Scale bars: A, B = 2 mm; C = 0.5 mm; D = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178173/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Figs. 
<number box="[1312,1326,1301,1327]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
A, B). The pleuron of pleonite 
<number box="[439,454,1341,1367]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="4.0">4</number>
is rounded in its terminal portion, while pleonite 
<number box="[1047,1061,1341,1367]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="5.0">5</number>
has a developed terminal spine (
<figureCitation box="[159,233,1381,1407]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,255,1770,1794]" captionTargetBox="[151,1429,356,1724]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,354,1746]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879), ovigerous (MZUESC  714), from Camamu Bay, Bahia, Brazil. A. anterior region of carapace, lateral view; B. carapace and cephalic appendages, dorsal view; C. right outer antennular flagellum; D. abdomen and telson, lateral view. Scale bars: A, B = 2 mm; C = 0.5 mm; D = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178173/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Fig. 
<number box="[218,233,1381,1407]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
D). The telson tip has 
<number box="[509,524,1381,1407]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="6.0">6</number>
terminal spines, and their position and length are as described by 
<bibRefCitation pageId="17" pageNumber="44" refString="Udekem d'Acoz, C. d'. (2000) Redescription of Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879) based on topotypical specimens, with remarks on Lysmata seticaudata (Risso, 1816) (Decapoda, Caridea, Hippolytidae). Crustaceana, 73 (6), 719 - 735." type="journal article">
Udekem d’Acoz (
<number box="[254,319,1421,1447]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="2000.0">2000</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. The stylocerite overreaches the outer border of the basal antennular peduncle (
<figureCitation box="[1274,1346,1421,1447]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,255,1770,1794]" captionTargetBox="[151,1429,356,1724]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,354,1746]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879), ovigerous (MZUESC  714), from Camamu Bay, Bahia, Brazil. A. anterior region of carapace, lateral view; B. carapace and cephalic appendages, dorsal view; C. right outer antennular flagellum; D. abdomen and telson, lateral view. Scale bars: A, B = 2 mm; C = 0.5 mm; D = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178173/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Fig. 
<number box="[1330,1346,1421,1447]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
B). The accessory branch of the outer antennular flagellum consists of 
<number box="[890,905,1461,1487]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="4.0">4</number>
segments (
<figureCitation box="[1039,1109,1461,1487]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="18.[151,255,1770,1794]" captionTargetBox="[151,1429,356,1724]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,354,1746]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 5. Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879), ovigerous (MZUESC  714), from Camamu Bay, Bahia, Brazil. A. anterior region of carapace, lateral view; B. carapace and cephalic appendages, dorsal view; C. right outer antennular flagellum; D. abdomen and telson, lateral view. Scale bars: A, B = 2 mm; C = 0.5 mm; D = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178173/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Fig. 
<number box="[1094,1109,1461,1487]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
C). The merus of pereiopod 
<number box="[151,166,1501,1527]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="3.0">3</number>
is provided with 
<number box="[373,388,1501,1527]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="5.0">5</number>
lateral and 
<number box="[527,542,1501,1527]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="3.0">3</number>
ventral spines (
<figureCitation box="[729,800,1501,1527]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="19.[151,255,1642,1666]" captionTargetBox="[225,1351,183,1612]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[203,1488,183,1643]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 6. Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879), ovigerous (MZUESC  714), from Camamu Bay, Bahia, Brazil. A. left pereiopod 1; B. right pereiopod 2; C. right pereiopod 3; D. right pereiopod 4; E. same, dactyl; F. right pereiopod 5. Scale bars: A – D, F = 1 mm; E = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178174/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Fig. 
<number box="[784,800,1501,1527]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
C); pereiopod 
<number box="[970,984,1501,1527]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="4.0">4</number>
with 
<number box="[1052,1067,1501,1527]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="4.0">4</number>
lateral and 
<number box="[1206,1221,1501,1527]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1.0">1</number>
ventral (
<figureCitation box="[1327,1398,1501,1527]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="19.[151,255,1642,1666]" captionTargetBox="[225,1351,183,1612]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[203,1488,183,1643]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 6. Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879), ovigerous (MZUESC  714), from Camamu Bay, Bahia, Brazil. A. left pereiopod 1; B. right pereiopod 2; C. right pereiopod 3; D. right pereiopod 4; E. same, dactyl; F. right pereiopod 5. Scale bars: A – D, F = 1 mm; E = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178174/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Fig. 
<number box="[1382,1398,1501,1527]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
D); and pereiopod 
<number box="[328,343,1541,1567]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="5.0">5</number>
with only 
<number box="[473,487,1541,1567]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="2.0">2</number>
lateral spines (
<figureCitation box="[669,741,1541,1567]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="19.[151,255,1642,1666]" captionTargetBox="[225,1351,183,1612]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[203,1488,183,1643]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 6. Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879), ovigerous (MZUESC  714), from Camamu Bay, Bahia, Brazil. A. left pereiopod 1; B. right pereiopod 2; C. right pereiopod 3; D. right pereiopod 4; E. same, dactyl; F. right pereiopod 5. Scale bars: A – D, F = 1 mm; E = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178174/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Fig. 
<number box="[725,741,1541,1567]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
F). The propodus of pereiopod 
<number box="[1113,1128,1541,1567]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="3.0">3</number>
has 
<number box="[1185,1199,1541,1567]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="9.0">9</number>
ventral spines (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="19.[151,255,1642,1666]" captionTargetBox="[225,1351,183,1612]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[203,1488,183,1643]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 6. Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879), ovigerous (MZUESC  714), from Camamu Bay, Bahia, Brazil. A. left pereiopod 1; B. right pereiopod 2; C. right pereiopod 3; D. right pereiopod 4; E. same, dactyl; F. right pereiopod 5. Scale bars: A – D, F = 1 mm; E = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178174/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,167,1581,1607]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
C). The dactyli of pereiopods 
<number box="[517,561,1581,1607]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3–5</number>
are armed with 
<number box="[752,766,1581,1607]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="5.0">5</number>
spines (
<figureCitation box="[863,934,1581,1607]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="19.[151,255,1642,1666]" captionTargetBox="[225,1351,183,1612]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[203,1488,183,1643]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 6. Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879), ovigerous (MZUESC  714), from Camamu Bay, Bahia, Brazil. A. left pereiopod 1; B. right pereiopod 2; C. right pereiopod 3; D. right pereiopod 4; E. same, dactyl; F. right pereiopod 5. Scale bars: A – D, F = 1 mm; E = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178174/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Fig. 
<number box="[918,934,1581,1607]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
E). However, our specimen differs in some important aspects from typical specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[676,834,1621,1646]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intermedia">
<emphasis box="[676,834,1621,1646]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">L. intermedia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The merus of pereiopod 
<number box="[1136,1151,1621,1647]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="2.0">2</number>
is subdivided in 
<number box="[1350,1379,1621,1647]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="16.0">16</number>
segments, while the carpus has 
<number box="[489,518,1661,1687]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="23.0">23</number>
(
<figureCitation box="[536,619,1661,1687]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="19.[151,255,1642,1666]" captionTargetBox="[225,1351,183,1612]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[203,1488,183,1643]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 6. Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879), ovigerous (MZUESC  714), from Camamu Bay, Bahia, Brazil. A. left pereiopod 1; B. right pereiopod 2; C. right pereiopod 3; D. right pereiopod 4; E. same, dactyl; F. right pereiopod 5. Scale bars: A – D, F = 1 mm; E = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178174/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Figs. 
<number box="[603,619,1661,1687]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
B). Therefore, the number of segments of the carpus is less than that reported by 
<bibRefCitation box="[294,579,1701,1727]" pageId="17" pageNumber="44" refString="Udekem d'Acoz, C. d'. (2000) Redescription of Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879) based on topotypical specimens, with remarks on Lysmata seticaudata (Risso, 1816) (Decapoda, Caridea, Hippolytidae). Crustaceana, 73 (6), 719 - 735." type="journal article">
Udekem d’Acoz (
<number box="[505,570,1701,1727]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="2000.0">2000</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<number box="[591,668,1701,1727]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="28.0" valueMax="31.0" valueMin="25.0">25–31</number>
, more commonly 
<number box="[882,960,1701,1727]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="29.0" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="28.0">28–30</number>
. Also, only 
<number box="[1103,1118,1701,1727]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1.0">1</number>
ventral spine is present on the ventral margin of pereiopod 
<number box="[534,551,1741,1767]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="4.0">4</number>
, whereas in the topotypical material examined by that author, 
<number box="[1291,1305,1741,1767]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="2.0">2</number>
(occasionally 
<number box="[203,218,1781,1807]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="3.0">3</number>
) spines are found. Finally, the telson tip is rounded, not ending in a terminal blunt apical tooth as indicated by 
<bibRefCitation box="[264,555,1821,1847]" pageId="17" pageNumber="44" refString="Udekem d'Acoz, C. d'. (2000) Redescription of Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879) based on topotypical specimens, with remarks on Lysmata seticaudata (Risso, 1816) (Decapoda, Caridea, Hippolytidae). Crustaceana, 73 (6), 719 - 735." type="journal article">
Udekem d’Acoz (
<number box="[481,546,1821,1847]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="2000.0">2000</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. The closest related species to 
<taxonomicName box="[937,1099,1821,1846]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intermedia">
<emphasis box="[937,1099,1821,1846]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">L. intermedia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the warm–temperate 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seticaudata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">L. seticaudata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Dohrn &amp; Holthuis, 1950" authorityName="Dohrn &amp; Holthuis" authorityYear="1950" box="[350,754,1861,1887]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nilita">
<emphasis box="[350,446,1861,1886]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">L. nilita</emphasis>
Dohrn &amp; Holthuis, 
<number box="[695,754,1861,1887]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="1950.0">1950</number>
</taxonomicName>
from the northeast Atlantic and the Mediterranean. The other species currently recognized in the Atlantic are not closely related. 
<taxonomicName box="[1030,1265,1901,1926]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intermedia">
<emphasis box="[1030,1265,1901,1926]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Lysmata intermedia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from the other two species mainly by the fewer segments in the accessory branch of the outer antennular flagellum (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Udekem" box="[395,656,1981,2007]" pageId="17" pageNumber="44" refString="Udekem d'Acoz, C. d'. (2000) Redescription of Lysmata intermedia (Kingsley, 1879) based on topotypical specimens, with remarks on Lysmata seticaudata (Risso, 1816) (Decapoda, Caridea, Hippolytidae). Crustaceana, 73 (6), 719 - 735." type="journal article" year="2000">
Udekem d’Acoz 
<number box="[597,656,1981,2007]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
for more details). The differences between our material and those described for topotypical specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[623,783,152,177]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intermedia">
<emphasis box="[623,783,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">L. intermedia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
suggest the possibility that our specimen belongs to a closely related, undescribed species of 
<taxonomicName box="[608,706,192,217]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[608,706,192,217]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Lysmata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,152,298]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">The occurrence of this species in Camamu Bay partially fills the gap in its range along the northeastern and eastern Brazilian coast, between the states of Pernambuco and Espírito Santo.</paragraph>
